        </h1>
        <div class="flex items-center text-lg mb-8">
          <time datetime="2026-03-01">March 1, 2026</time>
          <span class="mx-4">&bull;</span>
          <span>11 min read</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed">
          Tacoma cut violent crime by <strong>17% in 2024</strong>. That's real progress. But walk through downtown, visit Point Defiance Park after dark, or talk to business owners along East 25th Street, and you'll hear a different story. Only <strong>24% of residents</strong> say they feel safe in downtown Tacoma. Here's what's actually happening on the ground, where the biggest gaps are, and what's working to close them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Answer Section -->
    <QuickAnswer
      question="How safe are Tacoma's public spaces in 2025-2026?"
      answer="Tacoma recorded 22,230 total crimes in 2024, giving residents a 1-in-12 chance of becoming a property crime victim. While overall violent crime dropped 17.3% in 2024, specific public spaces remain problem areas. Point Defiance Park experienced 5 assaults and 1 sexual assault in 2024. South Park suffered $400,000 in vandalism damage. Only 24% of residents feel safe downtown. The city's Violent Crime Reduction Plan — developed with UT San Antonio researchers — produced a 19% drop in street crimes in target areas, and the city is now expanding surveillance camera authority to parks and public zones under HB 2384. Mobile surveillance trailers offer a flexible, rapid-deployment option for covering parks, trailheads, and public facilities where permanent cameras haven't been installed yet."
    />

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6 max-w-4xl">
        <div class="blog-content prose prose-lg max-w-none">

          <!-- Stats Section -->
